{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:02:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:02:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15347"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15347"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0,0.04,0.25,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8038"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92926"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8038"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76278"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4836"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23389"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92926"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA parent brings their six-year-old child to the general practitioner with a three-month history of infrequent, hard stools and occasional soiling. The parent requests an X-ray to confirm constipation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about abdominal X-rays in childhood constipation is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal X-rays deliver 35-50 times the radiation of chest X-rays","Abdominal X-rays are required to diagnose constipation","Abdominal X-rays should confirm treatment success","Abdominal X-rays are needed if history is unclear","Abdominal X-rays help determine stool burden"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal X-rays are not routinely indicated for the diagnosis or monitoring of childhood constipation. Clinical history and physical examination are the primary diagnostic tools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey points:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E deliver approximately 35-50 times the radiation dose of a chest X-ray, making radiation exposure an important consideration in children\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E for diagnosis are not necessary when history is suggestive of constipation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E should not be used to confirm treatment success\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehistory is unclear\u003C/strong\u003E, focus should be on detailed clinical assessment rather than imaging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Estool burden\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen on X-ray, this finding does not change clinical management in most cases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of constipation in children should be based on clinical features including stool frequency, consistency, and associated symptoms such as soiling or withholding behaviours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal X-rays are not routinely indicated for diagnosis or monitoring of childhood constipation.","An abdominal X-ray delivers approximately 35-50 times the radiation dose of a chest X-ray.","Clinical history and examination are the primary tools for diagnosing childhood constipation."],"references":["Bolia R, Safe M, Southwell BR, King SK, Oliver MR. Paediatric constipation for general paediatricians: Review using a case-based and evidence-based approach. J Paediatr Child Health. 2020 Nov;56(11):1708-1718. doi: 10.1111/jpc.14720. PMID: 33197982","Constipation in children and young people: diagnosis and management. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2017 Jul. (NICE Clinical Guidelines, No. 99.) Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554924/","Pawasarat A, Biank VF. Constipation in Pediatrics: A Clinical Review. Pediatr Ann. 2021 Aug;50(8):e320-e324. doi: 10.3928/19382359-20210714-01. Epub 2021 Aug 1. PMID: 34398719","Knight AL, Howlett DC. Imaging of the acute abdomen. Surgery (Oxford). 2010 Nov;28(11):568-574. Available from: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0263931910001778?casa_token=K3H4jYtwgy0AAAAA:rpBR_8bbucSqz8LVT0lHAUXEWr8z5wqVKsxYD7oHgJo-xG0bfJmUqN-027rWCDO3REfqwhp679o","Chawla, A., \u0026 Peh, W. C. G. (2018). Abdominal radiographs in the emergency department: current status and controversies. Journal of medical radiation sciences, 65(4), 250\u2013251. https://doi.org/10.1002/jmrs.307"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76278"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15347"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76278"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T22:03:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T10:43:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8038"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevi